Moreover, we might integrate *temporal resolution preservation* as an explicit objective during training, perhaps via auxiliary losses that encourage gradient flow across critical time steps, or by maintaining a thin "high-resolution backbone" through select layers.

One innovative angle would be to couple this with *computationally adaptive inference*: simpler utterances trigger faster path through the funnel, while complex ones retain longer sequences in higher layers—enabling variable latency with consistent accuracy.

This approach could significantly advance streaming ASR and edge-device deployment, where both low latency and high accuracy are paramount. It also opens theoretical questions about the *information bottleneck* in speech representations—when and where temporal detail can be safely discarded.

